notes: In comparison to cGMP-bound mouse PDE2A (12271124)
“Phosphorylation of Ser913/Thr914 would disturb the contact between the R domain of one monomer and the adjacent P domain.”(34757782)

“The flipped DFG motif moves the aspartate away from the ATP binding site by ∼5 Å, leading to a catalytically incompetent state termed the “DFG-out” state.” ( 25478866) “ALM301 binds in an allosteric pocket created by the combined movement of the PH domain and the catalytic domain, resulting in a DFG out conformation.” (36127435) On visual investigation, it appears a loop at ~ residue 81 occludes the active site in the native structure and pushes the DFG into an “out” state as well as displaces the alpha helix with residue 195.
Enzyme forms a dimer in vivo and the Bateman modules (region 1) interact in a trans fashion with the enzyme’s active site. (25197074)

Importantly, this is actually in an inhibitor-induced conformation where the molecule is not catalytically active. “As a result of the change in position of helix C, the side chain of the highly conserved glutamate residue Glu114 (equivalent to Glu91 in PKA) is shifted away from the active site and is unable to form a critical ion pair with the conserved catalytic Lys97 (equivalent to Lys72 in PKA)” (15543157). This is also the only structure of MEK2 in the PDB that is not more than a few residues long.

organism: Methanocaldococcus jannaschii (strain ATCC 43067 / DSM 2661 / JAL-1 / JCM 10045 / NBRC 100440)
